blocks.text: Okay, so my name is Mark Boas – I am based in Italy and for the last 10 years or so have been obsessed with this project called Hyperaudio.
Hyperaudio has kind of grown with the Mozilla festival. I demonstrated a very simple version at the very first science fair in Barcelona. So it's more than 10 years old, I suppose. Doesn't time fly!

And so, you know, I've been to a lot of Mozilla Festivals and demonstrated it to various people, and I always kind of come back enthused. And so this year is no exception. And I'm going to just show you where we currently are with a little bit of history, what we've done and will invite questions and stuff. Now, we can stop at any point and talk about anything that you see.
I'm going to share the screen, so you can see what I'm seeing in my browser.
So if I can get that working.
It's not...
Can you all see my screen?
Yeah.
Yes, yes.
Yeah, that's great. So, actually, we're collaborating with MozFest this year as we did last year. We did a pilot.

First I suppose I should explain what Hyperaudio is. Hyperaudio is transcript powered audio and video for the web. What does transcript powered mean? It means that we transcribe video or audio, and we get a timed transcript back, and we use that to allow people to navigate media, share it and remix it.
And what this also does is give us increased accessibility. So once we have a timed transcript, we can create captions automatically, we can translate into other languages.

And so there's accessibility from the hearing point of view as well. People who have hearing issues can use Hyperaudio to allow them to access video, but also, you know, internationally, by translating we spread the love a bit amongst all the people of the world, and they can come and consume content, even if it's not there first language.
Also for for learning languages, it's really handy because you kind of see the words light up in a kind of karaoke way.

So we're just in the process of creating a version of Hyperaudio called Hyperaudio for Conferences, and this is what we're going to try out for MozFest. So the basic idea is to transcribe, translate, repurpose and share. But you can go go to that website at your leisure.
The thing I really wanted to show was what does an interactive transcript looked like.
And so I've got a few examples here.
One thing is that speech to text is good. It's getting better all the time. Certainly much better then it was when I first started doing this, but it's not perfect.
And so what we need, really is the ability to correct transcripts.
Now. I mentioned before that the timing is really important because we use that for the captions. And later on, I'll show you how we use that, actually for remixing purposes.
Dave – I've just seen you've joined – welcome!
We can use it for remixing purposes. So a lot of our work has been creating an editor that allows you to change the text but maintain the timings.

Also, you know, a speech to text algorithm won't necessarily pick up the different speakers it often has a go, but it won't know the names or anything like that. So we also allow people to assign speaker names and stuff like that. And so let me just give you a quick demo of this editor we're working on.
This is an open editor. It's open source. And it's something that we developed in partnership with The Studs Terkel Radio Archive in Chicago. So I can... let me just play it.
Let's see if we can get anything to play. Have to reload.
This is often the case school for live demos.

So the first thing you might notice is there's a bit of music in there and the speech to text algorithm has tried to transcribe it. But it's only come up with "uhms" and "yeahs", which is interesting. So that might be the first thing that you would delete, perhaps from a transcript is that sort of extraneous content.

So what you can do is just, you know, highlight and delete. So we'll go down... As you can see, straight away, you can scan through and get an idea of the content, which is one of the benefits of a transcript.

"...Deb Rajhi. Um and I am a Mozilla fellow studying algorithm auditing and evaluation. Um, I worked very closely with the Algorithmic Justice League initiative, which was founded by Joy Buolamwini at the MIT Media Lab..."

So it's done a pretty good job, but sometimes you want to do things like maybe remove disfluencies. I mean, this is kind of an editorial choice. Some people do, some people don't, and it's interesting talking to people to see what they do. But I can remove an "um" and, you know...
"...evaluation. Um, I worked very closely with the algorithmic Justice League initia.."

And so it carries on and keeps the timings. Often we want to assign a speaker. And so you can just put Deborah. And maybe we want to, you know, split that into a different paragraph, and so you can just do that.
And oops, there you go. And then you get, you know, the new timecode at the start. So that's just introduce you to part of the process of creating an interactive transcript.
And yeah, the speech to text engine does a lot, but you will definitely want to go in and correct that. When you're correcting. It would be great if you can also keep the timing.

So that's what we're going to offer as part of Hyperaudio for Conferences – is the ability for session facilitators to come in after their content is transcribed and come in and correct it. It would also be kind of cool if that could be kind of crowd sourced. You know, the great thing about Mozilla is a community. You would be able to do that much quicker if everybody kind of took a paragraph and went in and corrected it.

Otherwise, we're finding that depending on how the quality of the audio and the accent and that sort of thing and the quality of the speech to text, that might take you three or four times the length of the media to correct. So it's quite a job.
What you end up with is an interactive transcript. So this is one we did for the pilot last year.
"watching this video with... that video with Tamir Rice, where the young man who was killed by the police, uh, for carrying, I think like a toy gun and I was like, man, what if..."

So there you can see in English, but what we've also done... and you've also got a choice of captions as well. We've also had it translated into different languages. So if we go to Spanish you'll see that...
"man what if, you know, there was an opportunity to media and technology that could have..."

...you'll see the Spanish version. With the translated versions, we can kind of do word for word timings. So it kind of comes down to a kind of sentence level accuracy, which in this case, is actually caption level.
I think from the new version, we're going to go for sentences because it makes more sense to light up one sentence at a time rather than sort of caption viewW
We've also got the ability to kind of share.
"...but I was really passionate about..."

You know, audio and video is kind of it's kind of closed off. It's not necessarily very visible on the Web. It's not that easy to be able to share a small clip as we can do with text. But now we've got the text. We could definitely do that. And so the idea is that you highlight the text you're interested in. It puts that text into a tweet. And then there's a link directly back to that piece of the transcript.
Anybody got any questions at this stage?

I do have one question. I noticed that the transcript didn't translate... didn't transcribe Joy Buolamwini surname correctly. I wondered how, like, would... how your... how Hyperaudio translates, no transcribes African and African diasporan names. Yeah.
Sure, I think the idea is for the transcript and the translations. There's always going to be a humans come in and kind of check those. So in this case, this might not have been checked properly.

But we find that even with the automatic translation in the state of technology at the moment, there are errors. And that's where kind of humans come in to kind of cast an eye over things and check that things are okay.

In general, I... you know, I'm not I'm not sure what the common issues the speech to text engines are, but I suppose if we knew them, we could maybe have some hints or tips for people to check for certain things.
Is that is that kind of what you were asking Hillary?
Yeah, and I think you've answered it well, and I think the aspects of like, the human has to be involved. Yeah.
Okay, Yeah, I'll have a think about that as well.
Another interesting thing is music right? So we saw a bit of music get translated as transcribed as "ums" and "yeahs" and stuff. But we are very interested in this sort of musical aspect of audio.
And so this is an interactive transcript that's just experimental, which actually has a bit of audio inside it. Now, the way that we did this was to use a special font.

So this is text, but this is also text. But it's also a kind of sound wave and that will allow us later to be able to do things, if we wanted to, like remix music. But for us really is important to have some representation of sound that is not the spoken word, because sometimes you will have very sparsepieces of video or audio, where vast length of it might not be the spoken word. But you still want to be able to select and edit stuff. And so it would be, I think, an option that you could turn off and on. So this is kind of cool. So I'll just play a little bit of this
"...wonderfully atmospheric phrases played by the cellos and basses..."
So you can see it's all clickable. It's not very super clear that... which is being highlighted as it is with the text but you can see the principle at work.
And I think that would be kind of... I can imagine this being a nice sort of tutorial for people learning music.
Hold on. I need to move my zoom bar.
So one project we did with Hyperaudio... an important thing about Hyperaudio is not just a platform, it is an open source library as well.

And so we try and work with other people to implement solutions for them. And one of the stipulations is often that that gets released as open source. And that's how we managed to create that editoras as an open source piece of software.
And we did a great collaboration with the Studs Terkel Radio Archive, which is actually a Kickstarter, and so I just wanted to show a little bit of what we did there.

This is an interview with... I mean the content is so good. It's so interesting to work with amazing content, like the stuff that Studs Terkel produced. And this is, you know, this goes back many years and this is a 1962 interview, and it was really... it's really fascinating. So it was. It was a privilege to work with them, and the Kickstarter was successful. So this one's about... this is Eartha Kitt discussing her musical career. So let's just watch a bit of this or listen.

"Yes, it's town called Uskudura, and it was in Uskudura that this song, it was the little town of Uskudura that this song is about. Not only that, you know many people when I first made this record, they did not know that there was such a thing as a Turkish language, and I got a lot of fan mail, and but it was played on the air for the first time in the history of America they put a Turkish folk song in the American school books..."
"...that line, that gap between the childhood and the..."

So, there you can see, you know, this is a really nice representation of an interactive transcript. Obviously, somebody has put a lot of thought into the design. It wasn't actually us. We worked with designers, and somebody has spent a lot of time, kind of, editing that transcript because, you know, this is an important part of oral history.
We went further, and we created a remixer. And the idea was that this could be used by anybody really to create interesting mixes from different sources so I could get that very same transcript here.
"...you might call this a gay yet sardonic comment on our values I can go away and describe..."
And so this is the first view of a remixer. So we spoke about it briefly before, but we got the word timings. They seem to see them light up. So now we can start creating.
And we can put things together from different sources. So, I'm just typing things in a bit randomly here, but...

You don't have to take the whole paragraph. You can just take a word or two if you want. And we can put fades or trims in here. So the trim actually allows you to... because sometimes we don't know when the word actually finishes. We just have start times and the trim allows you to tweak things.

But just to show you this working – this is all audio. And in theory, we should have a poster here showing the person who's been interviewed. Somehow that got lost at some point. But it's really quite important because when you see things change from one person to another.
"...order and so forth."
"Yes, because I think that no matter which song I am singing..."
And that looks like one continuous piece of audio. But actually it's just a playlist of two different pieces of audio. We don't mix down to one file
Again. I'll pause then here for any questions.
This is a licencing question. I have, what are the text licence on those? I'm intrigued.
What's the copyright?
Yeah.
Well, luckily, the Studs Terkel Radio archive, they own the copyright to it, but they are quite protective about their content.
You could I imagine copy and paste text very easily into a document.
But it is something that we think about. I was talking to lawyers the other day about, you know, is a derivative work of a piece of audio, If you transcribe it, is it subject to copyright?
You know what? If you hand transcribe it, when does it stop becoming notes? When does it become a copyright issue? And it's it's kind of a grey area. I don't know the answer actually.
Hillary, have you come across any...

I don't know the answer as well. Partly because, like, if let's say, for example...  I'm not a lawyer, so I don't have legal expertise to give legal advice. But I know it can be... you can submit works into different licences if anyone if you only could be right. But it can be quite hard if you don't have the access to the person who actually owns the copyright or it's not clear who does. But yeah, that's all I wanted to say.
Yeah.

Cool. So that was a really nice thing. And they they've tried. They've taken this remixer of into communities, libraries, and they had a different kind of competitions where people could put together remixes. It's an educational thing as well, and we might talk about that a bit later on – the educational aspect.

We also did some work for Al Jazeera, where they had a lot of documentaries on Palestine. They were in various languages, and so this was our first experience of working with right to left languages such as Arabic, and we've got Hebrew as well, and they basically ran a competition.
The difference with this one is...

... is that we only allow whole paragraphs to be selected. Part of this is to do with the fact that we don't have necessarily the word timings because we don't have the original language represented. And so you know, it's the same issues of translation we saw before.

But also we have to be careful about misrepresentation, especially with such a sensitive subject. And you know, if people just take one word or two words from here and there, they could build up something that does misrepresent.

Luckily, with Hyperaudio, we always have the context there and what we're trying to do with high profile conferences that first and foremost so that, you know, it's almost impossible to see a remix without having to, you know, without seeing the actual sources as well since we have them so you can imagine, on the right hand side, your remix will be playing, but the left hand side will switch to the actual source of that particular clip at any one time, and I think that's kind of useful.
I wonder if we have if I can easily show you Arabic. I think once you're in...
I'm just gonna say, Mark is there maybe some of the links to drop in the chat if people want to open them for later, even to play.
Yeah, that's a great point. Yeah, so I'll kind of backfill afterwards. But I'll put some of the previous ones in.
Okay, Thank you.
And you let me just do this one. Did you do the Studs Terkel one – yeah you've done that one. Okay, so there was this demo – audio demo and I think that's referenced. Yeah. And the editor.
If you if you need access to an editor, let me know and that can be arranged. So the only issue with editors is that the transcription costs something.

So another interesting thing we did... this is the old version of Hyperaudio. Now we're making a new one, so this is a slightly different domain. It's hyperaud dot io. This is before I think the dot audio domains came out. As soon as dot audio came out, we were like, quick get hyper.audio. So that's where a new one is going to be.

But we've actually taken Hyperaudio into schools as a tool for teaching media literacy, and I actually... you know, I'm based in Italy, so I took it into an Italian school. They said they wanted all the content in English because they wanted to help them learn English at the same time as the sort of media literacy literacy side. And the reason why we're thinking that it's useful for mediaa literacy is because the context is always there, and that's important. But it's just such a simple way of mixing media that kids can pick it up straight away, and it's kind of very intuitive.
And so we did something on the climate crisis. You can you can play with this yourself and I'll just put it in here.

We have different versions of Hyperaud.io. We have the kind of top level, which has so much media, and anyone could just put anything in there so that, you know it's really basically a tech demo our first version. It's not commercialised or anything like that.
So we had these sub domains and schools is one of them, and it's got much less content on it, far fewer pieces. So just to show you this working...
"...to know about this, she just and we are supporting help  for our benefits only"
"...the amount of new knowledge 6000 publications as..."

So, what you can do again is just the usual drag and drop and choose from different sources. And then you just kind of build up a remix. And so we split the kids into groups and tried this out... and you can put a title in

"...impressed by the amount of new knowledge 6000 publications assessed in the report, and what comes out is a clean water. Temperatures also cause a lot of the ice to melt and it ends up in the ocean..."

So, yeah, that's a really fun tool for kids to use. And we had a lot of success. It's something that we're looking at for the future is this idea that we can use hyper audio as a tool for kids to use and learn? But we need to work with educators to make sure... you know we're noteducators were technologists.

And so we need to work with people that really know about teaching in schools. And another interesting bit is that you could add background music, which I really like because music is really important in portraying... sending a message to people. And, you know, when people are affected by media, then they sometimes don't realise why. And it can be something to start those music. There was an Amazon advert where it was quite happy and bouncy, and then somebody put some quite sad music in the background and suddenly became a very more sinister piece. And I kind of showed the kids this in the school, to kind of illustrate how music is important.
So you just put your music here. Very straightforward duration and, in theory, that music would start.
"...and I'm impressed by the amount of new knowledge impressed by the amount of 6000 publications assessed in the report..."'
So that's that. And feel free to have a play with that at your own leisure.

This is our new one. This is our new... And you can see the difference of 10 years development. Style's definitely change. Not that I dislike the old one. I think it's quite cheery and fun to use the new ones a bit more, a bit more serious.

So this is what we're working on right now. So the Mozilla Festival will have their own URL, which will be mozfest dot hyper.audio. And all the sessions that we transcribe and have corrected and translated will be available to remix. And we've also built in the Web Monetisation so that speakers... each speaker can have a payment pointer. So when you're listening to that particular speaker, they are being strength streamed the payment.

So this, you know, this is this looks slightly different. It's got a different looking feel. And we're also using HLS, which is an adaptive streaming format of video. This means basically that if somebody has a poor Internet connection they can still consume it. And actually, I really want to try with very low quality video and audio because the transcript kind of carries it. You can almost imagine it when you see the words lit up in time, you know what the person is saying. You know – the kind of brain fills in, and this could be really useful for places where, you know, they don't really have high bandwidth, so low bandwidth areas or, you know, it's expensive or whatever.
And HLS also allows us to be very efficient in skipping from one piece to another so we found it really sort of smooth, to move from one place to another, and that helps with the remixes I think.
You know we can have... It's just very experimental and I keep losing the video. Yeah, I think I'll just leave that now. Where did the video? Here it comes.
"...I lead a research group called Space Enabled. Our work is to advance justice..."
So maybe it will work. It's not quite selecting the right...
"...alternative ways of saying how to lead a research group called..."
It's kind of working.

So that's what people who use Hyperaudio for the conference can expect to see something a bit more, I suppose, polished. I think the other one is okay, but this is good, too. And these are all your different sources here. And you know, you can give a remix of type and we have the same small things. We have transitions, transitions was something we also showed in schools, and the ability to add slides as well to a transcript which is useful for conferences.

So I said before that Hyperaudio isn't just a platform. It's also open source software. This is MIT licenced Hyperaudio Lite, which is very small, lightweight library that allows you to create interactive transcripts and you can link to YouTube. You can link to Soundcloud. You can do that sort of thing.

And you can actually have fun with this in ways that maybe, you know, just your imagination is really the limit. So this is a track by Kae Tempest that I thought I would just try and transcribe, and see how it when he's kind of spoken word singing. I suppose it is more spoken. I don't know what they call it, but it's, um I'm showing my age. But I like it. And so I thought I would try. And this is This is how it turned out.

"...made pacts".
So you can use it for artistic purposes as well.

And this is something that I put on a Glitch, and the code is there for anybody to kind of edit and look at. There's really not that much to it. If you're a developer, it was really a lot about a lot of it was really about CSS, this kind of styling of it.
Any questions?

It just looks so cool. I love the way that it just appears, to do with a spoken word are sort that, you know, it just brings it to life. I have a question. If it's... I looked into this years ago in terms of research into literacy, literacy interventions and close captioning was shown to be very successful intervention in many developing contexts. Where you were talking about, you know, where you've got low bandwidth.

And I know that in India, some of the broadcasters went for close captioning on national broadcasts, networks as a government intervention or as a, you know, turning things that are basically on TV into things that have captions as a way to sort of basically improve people's ability to read and learn to read. I don't know. Ah, you were talking about educational. I wonder. I mean, I don't know if you if you explored that sort of thing or whether that was something that, you know had popped up in the years.

Yeah, definitely. It was interesting to see that Winnie the Pooh's copyright had expired, and I thought that would be a great thing to make into a sort of interactive transcript type book. You know that you can either read or you can listen to. And if you click on the words, they get repeated to you and conceivably having two languages. So my partner is Italian.

Actually, she learned most of her English by watching daytime TV with the subtitles on so I you know, I've seen it in action. But maybe, you know, she would do the Italian version, and I would do the English version, and that would be really handy. Especially if you could kind of swap in real time and just check a word or at least a sentence in Italian, for, you know, teaching kids say English in this case. So yeah, I think I think that's a really valid application.

I mean, I'm even wondering, like, is it possible to have a sort of shazam type thing that you so you could potentially just pick up and  sort of use it like like a kind of way to... Would it work if you, if you were able to have an app that helps. Or is that too much of an ask or...?

So one thought I had was an extension, you know, Pocket and is actually owned by Mozilla. Now, I think allows you to bookmark usually text articles, web pages, right? And then it represents them, sometimes in its own way, inside the Pocket App on the Pocket website. I would love to create an extension that does the same for audio and video. So, you know, you just click a button and it saves the transcript as well as the video into your own sort of personal space, which allows you later to search it.

You know, you don't necessarily have to correct transcripts to get useful search function from them. I don't think right, Mostly it will work that gets most of the words, right, unless it's a kind of a weird phrase or something. So... and often things are repeated as well, so I think it would still be useful. Though it would be nice to allow people to correct. And I think it would still be useful without the correction. I think that would be really cool. I can imagine myself using it. So I've been scratching my own itch, I wonder how many other people would find that useful.
So I've been trying to get hold of Pocket and tell them about this and say, you know, "have you thought about this?", but no response yet, and that would be definitely an interesting project.

So another thing is the WordPress plug in, which uses Hyperaudio. So here we get down to the nitty gritty. This is also open source, but it's a AGPL this time so that I might do, because we don't want people to kind of, you know, just kind of sell it. WordPress plug ins are a thing that can be sold.
And so I've done some videos on how to use it, but basically, we use something called a Shortcode, and you can embed YouTube and you also need to be able to put the data in.

So let's see, if you go to settings -> Hyperaudio, you have this bit as well, which allows you to... It tells you how to use it. It tells you the data format so you can see there is an example  where every... It's HTML the transcript is basically represented in HTML. So people already who already know HTML or XML can pick it up quite easily. You have a start time, you have a duration, and there's various things you can pass through. You can tell it to generate captions. You can also tell it to the Web. Monetization. But you need that data, right?

So unfortunately, we can't build speech to text into the WordPress Plug in, so you can get that data in various formats. You can use, even a subtitle file if you've already got it. Our own open editor that we saw earlier has JSON. Speechmatics is somebody who provide services – speech-to-text. Gentle is a tool, a free tool that you can use online.
Hillary, I don't know if you've heard of Gentle – you come across that?
No I haven't. I'd love to hear more.

Yeah, I should... I'll put that link in. What Gentle does is... It's based on Kaldi, which is a speech-to-text engine, but it basically allows you to align text if you've already got it. But if you don't have any text, it will have a go at transcribing it. Only unfortunately, in English, but it's it's totally free. Let me see if I can just get a quick link to that. Lower Quality Gentle okay, so that we can... And that's also on GitHub.

So, back to this, you would get your data. You paste it in here, and then you have... I should have got something ready, but I haven't unfortunately, then you would get a markup view of it, which is just the HTML which you can tweak and rendered view which you can also kind of tweak as well.

So it's a very crude way of getting your data in, and it does rely on you having it in some format already. But we're probably going to try and improve the formats that we support in future to make that easier for people.
And so this is kind of what you get from from that. So this is a WordPress installation, and we've got...
And here is a version where looking at the short code, I formatted it so you can kind of see how things work. We kind of have paragraphs. And then the words within it.

And with Web Monetization, you can actually put payment pointers in here and it will switch when that person is speaking, or you can put it higher up. So if no person has a payment pointer it kind of cascades up the way. So that's the That's the WordPress plug in.
So there's a few things on the Hyperaudio... Even the platform that we're building is open source. And there's Hyperaudio Lite as well.
So really sort of coming to the end of things now. Yeah. So this is the one that we were editing. So this edited one here, so you can see the different speakers and so on.

And I would like to think that because Mozilla is such a great community that if they want things translated into different languages, the actual translation correction is quicker than the original.

You know, once you've got it in a good format, that format is maintained through translation. So it's just really correcting those weird words and turn of phrase that the automatic translation has done right?

So you can imagine groups of people... you have a translatorthon – that's a terrible word I know, but you know what I mean? You can get people round and just  knock these things out. But it would be great to get these Mozilla sessions in different languages with the captions with the interactive transcript.

And also, you know, the idea of remixing – this fun concept of putting together supercuts or, you know, actual remixes of themed content. And putting the slides in there, it just makes things just that much more accessible and easier to navigate.
